{{Infobox ancient site | name =Mihata Kofun Cluster | native_name = 美旗古墳群 | native_name_lang = | image = Akaizuka Kofun, genshitsu-1.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Akaizuka Kofun burial chamber | map_type = Japan Mie Prefecture#Japan | map_alt = location in Japan | relief = 1 | map_caption = Mihata Kofun Cluster | map_size = 270px | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | coordinates = {{coord|34|39|43|N|136|08|04|E|display=inline, title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Nabari, Mie]], [[Japan]] | region = [[Kansai region]] | type = [[Kofun]] cluster | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | built = 4th to 6th century AD | abandoned = | epochs = [[Kofun period]] | cultures = | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = Yes (no public facilities) | Historic Site = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = {{box|background=white|align=center|wide=yes|border size=3px|border color=brown|text align=center|[[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]]}} }} The {{nihongo|'''Mihata Kofun Cluster'''|美旗古墳群||}} is a group of [[Kofun period]] [[kofun|Kofun]]s located in the Mihata neighborhood of the city of [[Nabari, Mie]] in the [[Kansai region]] of [[Japan]]. It was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1978.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/db/heritages/detail/216709|title=美旗古墳群|trans-title= Mihata Kofun Cluster|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2020}}</ref> It is the largest group of ''kofun'' in the [[Iga Province|Iga region]].
==Overview== The Mihata Kofun Cluster is located in the Nabari Basin, and currently consists of seven tumuli. Five of these are {{nihongo|''[[zenpō-kōen-fun]]''|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun}}, which are shaped like a keyhole, having one square end and one circular end, when viewed from above. One is a {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Round Kofun|lt=circular-type|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}} ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}), with a horizontal stone-lined [[burial chamber]], and one is a {{ill|Square Kofun|lt=square-type|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|12=draft}} ({{nihongo|''hōfun''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}). The oldest dates from the latter half of the 5th century AD and it is speculated that these were the graves of the pre-Yamato conquest chieftains of the [[Iga Province|Iga region]]. There were once more tumuli scattered around this vicinity, but the others have been lost to urban development. <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The 88 meter-long Tonozuka Kofun on the northeastern plateau edge is the oldest of the tumuli, from which fragments of horse fittings have been [[archaeological excavation|excavated]]. Approximately 300 meters to the southwest are the 100 meter Jōrōzuka Kofun and the Bishamonzuka Kofun, both of which have moats. Approximately 800 meters south of Bishamonzuka Kofun is the Umazuka Kofun which is the largest in the group with a total length of 142 meters. It has a moat 7 to 25 meters wide. A short distance to the east is the square Kozuka Kofun, and 600 meters southeast is the 55-meter long Kijinzuka Kofun, which has a shallow moat with a width of about 6 meters, and which is thought to date from the beginning of the 6th century. On the right bank of the Obata River, which is about 1.5 kilometers south of the Kijinzuka Kofun, is the Akaizuka Kofun, a circular Kofun with a diameter of about 30 meters. <ref name="Shiseki"/>
The Umazuka Kofun is about a five-minute walk from [[Mihata Station]] on the [[Kintetsu Osaka Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
